<?xml version="1.0" encoding="utf-8"?>

<section xml:id="sec-rounding-off-and-truncation-errors" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
    <title>Rounding off and Truncation Errors</title>
    <!--  -->
    <objectives component="outcomes">
        <introduction>
            <p>
            <dl>
                <li>
                    <title>Strand</title>
                    <p>
                        2.0 Measurement and Geometry
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <title>Sub-Strand</title>
                    <p>
                        2.1 Approximation and Errors
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <title>Specific Learning Outcomes</title> 
                    <p>
                        Compute round off and truncation errors from measurements
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li component="lesson-plan">
                    <title>Grade Level</title>
                    <p>
                        11
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li component="lesson-plan">
                    <title>Estimated Duration</title>
                    <p>
                        40 minutes
                    </p>
                </li>
            </dl>
            </p>
        </introduction>
    </objectives>

    <!-- [LP] Add guidance on activity -->

    <axiom component="lesson-plan">
        <title>Problem-Solving and Discovery</title>
        <dl>
            <li>
                <title>Suggested Time</title>
                <p>40 minutes</p>
            </li>
            <li>
                <title>Objective</title>
                <p>To visually discover how truncation always reduces values while rounding balances errors around a midpoint.</p>
            </li>
            <li>
                <title>Teacher's Role</title>
                <p>Move around the room to verify that groups are dividing their number line scale accurately. Ensure they draw arrows pointing the correct direction for both tasks.</p>
            </li>
        </dl>
    </axiom>

    <activity>
        <statement>
            <p>
                <term>In Groups</term> of <m>3 - 4</m>
            </p>
            <p>
                Find a blank page in your exercise book and draw a <m>10</m> cm large straight line across the middle of the page. Mark the start as <m>1.60</m> and the end as <m>1.70</m>.
            </p>
            <p>
                Divide the line equally <m>1</m> cm apart and mark every point as <m>1.61, 1.62, \dots, 1.69</m>. Onto the line, mark <m>1.67</m> using a star (*), this is the working measurement.
            </p>
            <p>
                Work through the following tasks in your group and record your answers in your exercise book.
            </p>
            <p>
                <ol marker="(a)">
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            <term>Task A (The chop rule):</term> Truncate <m>1.67</m> to <m>1</m> decimal place. Mark the point on the line using a dot (<m>\circ</m>) and draw an arrow from the working measurement to the truncated value.
                        </p>
                        <p>
                            What is the truncated value of <m>1.67</m> to <m>1</m> decimal place?
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            <term>Task B (The rounding rule):</term> Round off <m>1.67</m> to <m>1</m> decimal place. Mark the point on the line using a dot (<m>\circ</m>) and draw an arrow from the working measurement to the rounded value.
                        </p>
                        <p>
                            What is the rounded value of <m>1.67</m> to <m>1</m> decimal place?
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            <term>Task C {Comparison}:</term> Look at the lengths of the arows you drew in Task A and Task B. Which arrow is longer? Which method is more accurate?
                        </p>
                    </li>
                </ol>
            </p>

        </statement>
    </activity>

    <!-- [LP] Add guidance on structured lesson plan-->

    <axiom component="lesson-plan">
        <title>Structured Instruction</title>
        <p>
            <dl>
            <li>
                <title>Suggested Time</title>
                <p>
                    15 minutes
                </p>
            </li>
            <li>
                <title>Objective</title>
                <p>
                    To define the clear math rules and vocabulary for the errors learners saw on their group number lines.
                </p>
            </li>
            </dl>
        </p>
        <paragraphs>
            <title>Key Takeaways &amp; Teacher Connection</title>
            <ol>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        <alert>Connecting to Learner Work:</alert> Walk around and point to the arrows the groups drew in their books. Show them that the truncation arrow always points backward because chopping digits makes a number smaller. 
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        Show them that the rounding arrow can point forward or backward because rounding moves to the closest whole mark.
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        <alert>Explaining the Mistakes (Errors):</alert> Explain that an <term>Absolute Error</term> is just the physical distance or gap between the true number (the star) and the new number <m>\circ</m>. 
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        Explain that a <term>Percentage Error</term> turns that gap into a percentage to show how big the mistake is compared to the original size.
                    </p>
                </li>
            </ol>
        </paragraphs>
    </axiom>

    <insight>
        <p>
            <term>Rounding off</term> targets the closest available boundary level, keeping the distance to the approximation as small as possible. <term>Truncation</term> drops digits entirely, pushing numbers backward regardless of how close they were to the next unit level.
        </p>
        <p>
        To compute errors easily, we use two simple formulas:
        <md>
            <mrow> \text{Absolute Error}\; =  \amp\; |\text{Working Measurement} - \text{Approximate measurement}| </mrow>
            <mrow>\text{Percentage Error} \;= \amp \; \frac{\text{Absolute Error}}{\text{Working Measurement}} \times 100\%</mrow>
        </md>
    </p>
    <p>
        Find the absolute, relative, and percentage errors from the learners experience above.:
    </p>
    <p>
        <ol marker="(a)">
            <li>
                <p>
                    Truncation?
                </p>
            </li>
            <li>
                <p>
                    Rounding off?
                </p>
            </li>
        </ol>
    </p>
    </insight>

    <!-- Add further instruction (not in a block) to develop ideas as needed -->

    <xi:include href="../lesson-plan-templates/example-intro.ptx" />

    <!-- Add at least 3 examples -->

    <example>
        <statement> 
            <p>
                Miss Rachel measurement of a pencil length is <m>3.1416</m> cm. Find the percentage error in the length of the pencil if;
            </p>
            <p>
                <ol marker="(a)">
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            The length of the pencil is rounded off to <m>3</m> significant figures.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            The length of the pencil is truncated off to <m>3</m> significant figures.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            Relating the learner experience and the example, what insight can you draw about the relationship between rounding off and truncation errors?
                        </p>
                    </li>
                </ol>
            </p>
        </statement>
        <solution>
            <p>
                <ol marker="(a)">
                    <li>
                        <p>
                           Rounded off 
                        </p>
                        <p>
                        </p>
                        <p>
                            <md>
                                <mrow>\text {Rounded value}\; = \amp\; 3.14 </mrow>
                                <mrow> \text{absolute error}\; = \amp\; |3.1416 - 3.14| </mrow>
                                <mrow> = \amp\; 0.0016 </mrow>
                                <mrow> \text{absolute error}\; = \amp\; \frac{0.0016}{3.1416} </mrow>
                                <mrow> = \amp\; 0.000509 </mrow>
                                <mrow>\text{percentage error}\; = \amp\; 0.000509 \times 100\% </mrow>
                                <mrow> = \amp\; 0.0509\% </mrow>
                            </md>
                            
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            Truncated off
                        </p>
                        <p>
                            <md>
                                <mrow>\text {Truncated value}\; = \amp\; 3.14 </mrow>
                                <mrow> \text{absolute error}\; = \amp\; |3.1416 - 3.14| </mrow>
                                <mrow> = \amp\; 0.0016 </mrow>
                                <mrow> \text{absolute error}\; = \amp\; \frac{0.0016}{3.1416} </mrow>
                                <mrow> = \amp\; 0.000509 </mrow>
                                <mrow>\text{percentage error}\; = \amp\; 0.000509 \times 100\% </mrow>
                                <mrow> = \amp\; 0.0509\% </mrow>
                            </md>
                        </p>
                    </li>
                </ol>
            </p>
        </solution>
    </example>

    <example>
        <statement> 
            <p>
                Amani downloads an interactive digital textbook that takes up exactly <m>2.48\;\text{GB}</m> of storage space. Her phone's storage manager truncates this number to <m>1</m> decimal place to display it on a home screen widget.
            </p>
            <p>
                <ol marker="(a)">
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            What is the storage size value displayed on the widget?
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            Calculate the percentage error in the displayed value.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                </ol>
            </p>
        </statement>
        <solution>
            <p>
                <ol marker="(a)">
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            Truncating <m>2.48</m> to <m>1</m> decimal place means chopping off the final digit completely. The widget displays <m>2.4\;\text{GB}</m>.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            To calculate the percentage error, we first find the absolute error and then express it as a percentage of the true value.
                        </p>
                        <p>
                            <md>
                                <mrow> \text{Absolute Error}\; = \amp\; |2.48 - 2.4| </mrow>
                                <mrow> \text{Percentage Error}\; = \amp\; \frac{0.08}{2.48} \times 100\% </mrow>
                                <mrow>\approx \amp\; 3.23\%  </mrow>
                            </md>
                        </p>
                    </li>
                </ol>
            </p>
        </solution>
    </example>

    <example>
        <statement>
            <p>
                The precise measurement of a school sprint track lane boundary is found to be <m>100.55\;\text{meters}</m>. Calculate the percentage error introduced if the distance is recorded to <m>3</m> significant figures using:
            </p>
            <p>
                <ol marker="(a)">
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            Rounding off rule.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            Truncation rule.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                </ol>
            </p>
        </statement>
        <solution>
            <p>
                <ol marker="(a)">
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            Rounding rules dictate that we look at the <m>4^{th}</m> digit to determine whether to round the <m>3^{rd}</m> digit up or down. 
                        </p>
                        <p>
                            Since the  digit <m>4^{th}</m> is a <m>5</m>, we round the <m>3^{rd}</m> digit up from <m>0</m> to <m>1</m>, giving us an approximation of <m>101\;\text{meters}</m>.
                        </p>
                        <p>
                            <md>
                                <mrow> \text{Absolute Error}\; = \amp\; |100.55 - 101| </mrow>
                                <mrow> \text{Percentage Error}\; = \amp\; \frac{0.45}{100.55} \times 100\% </mrow>
                                <mrow> = \amp\; 0.45\% </mrow>
                            </md>
                            
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            Truncation rules dictate that we simply drop all digits after the <m>3^{rd}</m> significant figure, regardless of their value. This gives us an approximation of <m>100\;\text{meters}</m>.
                        </p>
                        <p>
                            <md>
                                <mrow> \text{Absolute Error}\; = \amp\; |100.55 - 100| </mrow>
                                <mrow> \text{Percentage Error}\; = \amp\; \frac{0.55}{100.55} \times 100\% </mrow>
                                <mrow> \approx \amp\; 0.55\% </mrow>
                            </md>
                            
                        </p>
                    </li>
                </ol>
            </p>
        </solution>
    </example>

    <xi:include href="../lesson-plan-templates/assessment-intro.ptx" />

    <!-- If STACK questions are included, uncomment this: -->

